('verbal', 'Reckless is to cautious as rude is to:', NULL, '["Mean", "Polite", "Loud", "Selfish"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Reckless is the opposite of cautious; rude is the opposite of polite.'),
('verbal', 'Dull is to sharp as dim is to:', NULL, '["Dark", "Night", "Bright", "Blind"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Dull is the opposite of sharp; dim is the opposite of bright.'),
('verbal', 'Microscope is to biologist as telescope is to:', NULL, '["Stars", "Astronomer", "Lens", "Scientist"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'A microscope is the key instrument of a biologist; a telescope is the key instrument of an astronomer.'),
('verbal', 'Trunk is to elephant as shell is to:', NULL, '["Ocean", "Pearl", "Turtle", "Crab"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'A trunk is the characteristic feature of an elephant; a shell is the characteristic feature of a turtle.'),
('verbal', 'Epidemic is to disease as avalanche is to:', NULL, '["Mountain", "Snow", "Storm", "Disaster"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'An epidemic is a widespread outbreak of disease; an avalanche is a widespread rush of snow.'),
('verbal', 'Prologue is to play as introduction is to:', NULL, '["Chapter", "Book", "Story", "Essay"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'A prologue comes at the beginning of a play; an introduction comes at the beginning of a book.'),
('verbal', 'Stingy is to generous as vague is to:', NULL, '["Uncertain", "Hidden", "Specific", "Confusing"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Stingy is the opposite of generous; vague is the opposite of specific.'),
('verbal', 'Carpenter is to wood as blacksmith is to:', NULL, '["Anvil", "Fire", "Metal", "Horseshoe"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'A carpenter shapes wood; a blacksmith shapes metal.'),
('verbal', 'Island is to ocean as oasis is to:', NULL, '["Water", "Desert", "Palm", "Sand"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'An island is a land mass surrounded by ocean; an oasis is a fertile spot surrounded by desert.'),
('verbal', 'Cowardly is to lion as clumsy is to:', NULL, '["Bear", "Ballerina", "Turtle", "Elephant"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'It is surprising for a lion to be cowardly (they are known for bravery); it is surprising for a ballerina to be clumsy (they are known for grace).'),
('verbal', 'Volume is to sound as speed is to:', NULL, '["Time", "Motion", "Distance", "Force"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Volume is a property that describes how loud sound is; speed is a property that describes how fast motion is.'),
('verbal', 'All mammals are warm-blooded. Whales are mammals. Whales are warm-blooded — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'All mammals are warm-blooded and whales are mammals, so whales must be warm-blooded. True.'),
('verbal', 'No vegetables are sweet. Carrots are vegetables. Carrots are not sweet — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Depends"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'The premise says no vegetables are sweet, and carrots are vegetables, so carrots are not sweet. True (within the logic of the premises).'),
('verbal', 'All athletes exercise daily. Some students are athletes. Some students exercise daily — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Impossible"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'The students who are athletes must exercise daily, so at least some students exercise daily. True.'),
('verbal', 'All planets orbit a star. Some moons orbit planets. Some moons orbit stars — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Impossible"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Moons orbit planets, but the premises don''t tell us whether moons also orbit stars. Uncertain.'),
('verbal', 'No honest person lies. Jordan is honest. Jordan does not lie — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Maybe"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Since no honest person lies and Jordan is honest, Jordan does not lie. True.'),
('verbal', 'Some painters are left-handed. All left-handed people write with their left hand. Some painters write with their left hand — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Painters who are left-handed write with their left hand, so at least some painters write with their left hand. True.'),
('verbal', 'All chefs can cook. Some chefs cannot bake. Some people who can cook cannot bake — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Impossible"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'The chefs who cannot bake can still cook (since all chefs can cook), so some people who can cook cannot bake. True.'),
('verbal', 'All rivers flow to the sea. The Amazon is a river. The Amazon flows to the sea — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'All rivers flow to the sea; the Amazon is a river; therefore the Amazon flows to the sea. True.'),
('verbal', 'Some doctors are scientists. All scientists publish research. Some doctors publish research — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Impossible"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Doctors who are scientists must publish research, so at least some doctors publish research. True.'),
('verbal', 'No nocturnal animal is active during the day. Owls are nocturnal. Owls are not active during the day — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Depends"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'By definition, no nocturnal animal is active during the day, and owls are nocturnal, so owls are not active during the day. True.'),
('verbal', 'All computers need electricity. Some tablets are computers. Some tablets need electricity — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Tablets that are computers need electricity, so at least some tablets need electricity. True.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Sonnet", "Villanelle", "Haiku", "Ballad"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'A sonnet, villanelle, and haiku all have strict formal requirements for length and structure. A ballad is a narrative poem with no fixed line count or syllable scheme.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Memoir", "Biography", "Autobiography", "Novel"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Memoir, biography, and autobiography are all true accounts of real lives; a novel is fiction.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Simile", "Metaphor", "Alliteration", "Paragraph"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Simile, metaphor, and alliteration are all figures of speech; a paragraph is a structural unit of writing.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Envy", "Greed", "Pride", "Courage"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Envy, greed, and pride are traditionally classified as vices; courage is a virtue.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Mercury", "Venus", "Moon", "Mars"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Mercury, Venus, and Mars are planets; the Moon is a natural satellite.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Soliloquy", "Monologue", "Dialogue", "Oration"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Soliloquy, monologue, and oration all involve a single speaker; dialogue involves two or more speakers.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Granite", "Marble", "Limestone", "Bronze"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Granite, marble, and limestone are all types of rock; bronze is a metal alloy.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Theorem", "Hypothesis", "Axiom", "Stanza"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Theorem, hypothesis, and axiom are all terms from logic or science; a stanza is a section of a poem.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Infer", "Deduce", "Speculate", "Conclude"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Infer, deduce, and conclude all mean to arrive at a judgment based on evidence or reasoning. Speculate means to guess or theorize without sufficient evidence — it does not require support.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Senate", "Parliament", "Congress", "Judiciary"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Senate, parliament, and congress are all legislative bodies; the judiciary is the court system — a separate branch.'),
('verbal', 'TRUCULENT most nearly means:', NULL, '["Timid", "Eager to argue or fight", "Reliable", "Wandering"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Truculent means eager to argue, fight, or be aggressive in a bad-tempered way.'),
('verbal', 'OBSEQUIOUS most nearly means:', NULL, '["Stubborn", "Curious", "Excessively eager to please", "Loud"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Obsequious means overly eager to serve or please — to the point of being insincere.'),
('verbal', 'INVETERATE most nearly means:', NULL, '["Occasional", "Deeply habitual", "Stubborn", "Curable"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Inveterate means having a habit or tendency so firmly established it is unlikely to change.'),
('verbal', 'PEDANTIC most nearly means:', NULL, '["Wise", "Overly focused on minor rules or details", "Childlike", "Patient"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Pedantic means excessively concerned with formal rules or small details, often in a way that is tiresome.'),
('verbal', 'LACONIC most nearly means:', NULL, '["Wordy", "Logical", "Using very few words", "Lazy"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Laconic means using as few words as possible — brief and to the point.'),
('verbal', 'INSIPID most nearly means:', NULL, '["Spicy", "Intelligent", "Lacking flavor or interest", "Offensive"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Insipid means lacking flavor, interest, or any quality that would make it stimulating — bland.'),
('verbal', 'PERFIDIOUS most nearly means:', NULL, '["Loyal", "Treacherous", "Fearless", "Dangerous"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Perfidious means guilty of betrayal — deceitful and treacherous.'),
('verbal', 'EQUIVOCAL most nearly means:', NULL, '["Fair", "Ambiguous", "Similar", "Balanced"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Equivocal means open to more than one interpretation — deliberately ambiguous or unclear.'),
('verbal', 'MAGNANIMOUS most nearly means:', NULL, '["Powerful", "Generous and forgiving", "Proud", "Famous"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Magnanimous means very generous, especially in forgiving insults or not being petty.'),
('verbal', 'MENDACIOUS most nearly means:', NULL, '["Accurate", "Threatening", "Dishonest", "Humble"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Mendacious means not telling the truth — lying.'),
('verbal', 'EPHEMERAL most nearly means:', NULL, '["Eternal", "Delicate", "Lasting only a short time", "Mysterious"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Ephemeral means lasting for a very short time — fleeting.'),
('verbal', 'TACITURN most nearly means:', NULL, '["Rude", "Silent by nature", "Logical", "Secretive"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Taciturn means a person who habitually says very little — naturally silent or reserved.'),
('verbal', 'GARRULOUS most nearly means:', NULL, '["Cheerful", "Excessively talkative", "Boastful", "Aggressive"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Garrulous means excessively talkative, especially about trivial things.'),
('verbal', 'RECONDITE most nearly means:', NULL, '["Recovered", "Hidden", "Obscure and little known", "Complex"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Recondite means not known by many people — obscure and dealing with little-known subjects.'),
('verbal', 'INTREPID most nearly means:', NULL, '["Reckless", "Fearless", "Cautious", "Stubborn"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Intrepid means fearlessly brave — showing no fear in the face of danger.'),
('verbal', 'CENSURE is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Criticize", "Punish", "Praise", "Condemn"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Censure means to express strong disapproval; praise means to express strong approval — direct opposites.'),
('verbal', 'VENERATE is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Worship", "Despise", "Honor", "Fear"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Venerate means to regard with great respect; despise means to regard with contempt — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'VERBOSE is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Wordy", "Eloquent", "Terse", "Loud"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Verbose means using more words than necessary; terse means brief and to the point — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'TRACTABLE is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Manageable", "Gentle", "Obstinate", "Simple"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Tractable means easy to deal with or manage; obstinate means stubbornly refusing to cooperate — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'CREDULOUS is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Naive", "Skeptical", "Trusting", "Ignorant"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Credulous means too willing to believe things; skeptical means unwilling to believe without evidence — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'PENURY is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Misery", "Poverty", "Wealth", "Debt"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Penury means extreme poverty; wealth means an abundance of money — direct opposites.'),
('verbal', 'CANDOR is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Honesty", "Deceit", "Kindness", "Openness"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Candor means frankness and honesty; deceit means dishonesty and hiding the truth — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'SERENE is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Peaceful", "Quiet", "Agitated", "Content"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Serene means calm and peaceful; agitated means troubled and disturbed — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'OPULENT is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Luxurious", "Rich", "Austere", "Expensive"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Opulent means ostentatiously rich or lavish; austere means severe and without luxury — opposites.'),
('verbal', 'ALACRITY is the opposite of:', NULL, '["Eagerness", "Speed", "Reluctance", "Energy"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Alacrity means eager willingness and speed; reluctance means unwillingness — they are opposites.'),
('verbal', 'Herald is to announce as arbiter is to:', NULL, '["Judge", "Argue", "Negotiate", "Punish"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, 'A herald''s function is to announce; an arbiter''s function is to judge disputes.'),
('verbal', 'Censure is to praise as condemn is to:', NULL, '["Blame", "Acquit", "Punish", "Accuse"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Censure is the opposite of praise; condemn is the opposite of acquit (to free from blame).'),
('verbal', 'Iconoclast is to tradition as rebel is to:', NULL, '["Revolution", "Order", "Freedom", "Change"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'An iconoclast attacks tradition; a rebel attacks established order — the same oppositional relationship.'),
('verbal', 'Dilettante is to expertise as novice is to:', NULL, '["Skill", "Beginner", "Learning", "Mastery"]'::jsonb, 3, 3, 'A dilettante lacks expertise; a novice lacks mastery — both describe someone without the quality named.'),
('verbal', 'Pariah is to society as exile is to:', NULL, '["Punishment", "Homeland", "Crime", "Prison"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'A pariah is rejected by society; an exile is banished from his or her homeland.'),
('verbal', 'Perjury is to oath as forgery is to:', NULL, '["Signature", "Crime", "Document", "Money"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Perjury is the act of lying while under oath; forgery is the act of falsifying a document.'),
('verbal', 'Ascetic is to luxury as miser is to:', NULL, '["Money", "Generosity", "Poverty", "Saving"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'An ascetic refuses or avoids luxury; a miser refuses or avoids generosity (giving money).'),
('verbal', 'Platitude is to originality as cliché is to:', NULL, '["Speech", "Freshness", "Poetry", "Language"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'A platitude lacks originality; a cliché lacks freshness — both describe worn-out expressions.'),
('verbal', 'Impetuous is to restraint as profligate is to:', NULL, '["Wealth", "Extravagance", "Thrift", "Spending"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'An impetuous person lacks restraint; a profligate person lacks thrift — both describe absence of the paired quality.'),
('verbal', 'Elegy is to mourning as ode is to:', NULL, '["Grief", "Celebration", "Rhythm", "Epic"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'An elegy expresses mourning; an ode expresses celebration or admiration.'),
('verbal', 'Sophist is to deception as charlatan is to:', NULL, '["Magic", "Fraud", "Wisdom", "Performance"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'A sophist is characterized by clever deception through argument; a charlatan is characterized by fraud — pretending to have skills they lack.'),
('verbal', 'Solvent is to debt as immunity is to:', NULL, '["Medicine", "Vaccine", "Disease", "Health"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Being solvent means freedom from debt; having immunity means freedom from disease.'),
('verbal', 'All virtuous acts are selfless. No selfish act is virtuous. Alex''s act was selfish. Alex''s act was virtuous — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Impossible"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The premises tell us no selfish act is virtuous; Alex''s act was selfish; therefore it was not virtuous. False.'),
('verbal', 'All philosophers question assumptions. Some scientists question assumptions. Some scientists are philosophers — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Both groups question assumptions, but that doesn''t mean the scientists who do so are philosophers. Uncertain.'),
('verbal', 'No coward has ever been awarded the Medal of Honor. Captain Rivera was awarded the Medal of Honor. Captain Rivera is a coward — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Since no Medal of Honor recipient is a coward and Rivera received it, Rivera is not a coward. False.'),
('verbal', 'All primary colors can mix to form secondary colors. Green is a secondary color. Green can be formed from primary colors — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, 'Green is a secondary color; secondary colors are formed from primary colors; therefore green can be formed from primary colors. True.'),
('verbal', 'Some poems rhyme. All haiku are poems. Some haiku rhyme — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'All haiku are poems, and some poems rhyme — but we can''t determine whether any of those rhyming poems are haiku specifically. Uncertain.'),
('verbal', 'No democracy allows one-person rule. Country X allows one-person rule. Country X is a democracy — true, false, or uncertain?', NULL, '["True", "False", "Uncertain", "Neither"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Since no democracy allows one-person rule and Country X allows it, Country X cannot be a democracy. False.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Soliloquy", "Apostrophe", "Aside", "Allegory"]'::jsonb, 3, 3, 'Soliloquy, apostrophe, and aside are all dramatic devices used in theater; allegory is a literary narrative technique, not a theatrical device.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Stoic", "Epicurean", "Utilitarian", "Empiricist"]'::jsonb, 3, 3, 'Stoic, Epicurean, and Utilitarian are all ethical philosophies focused on how to live; Empiricism is an epistemological theory about how we gain knowledge.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Anachronism", "Foreshadowing", "Flashback", "Euphony"]'::jsonb, 3, 3, 'Anachronism, foreshadowing, and flashback all relate to the manipulation of time in a narrative; euphony refers to pleasant sound patterns in writing.'),
('verbal', 'Which word does NOT belong with the others?', NULL, '["Hubris", "Hamartia", "Catharsis", "Soliloquy"]'::jsonb, 3, 3, 'Hubris, hamartia, and catharsis are all concepts from Aristotle''s theory of tragedy; a soliloquy is a theatrical speech technique, not a structural concept of tragedy.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  2, 4, 6, 8, ___', NULL, '["9", "10", "12", "11"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Adding 2 each time: 8 + 2 = 10.'),
('quantitative', 'A number multiplied by 3 gives 21. What is the number?', NULL, '["6", "9", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '21 ÷ 3 = 7.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  100, 90, 80, 70, ___', NULL, '["55", "65", "60", "50"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Subtracting 10 each time: 70 − 10 = 60.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  3, 6, 12, 24, ___', NULL, '["36", "42", "48", "30"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Each term doubles: 24 × 2 = 48.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 3/4  vs.  (B) 7/10. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, '3/4 = 0.75; 7/10 = 0.70. A is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is divided by 5, then 8 is added, giving 12. What was the original number?', NULL, '["20", "25", "15", "30"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, '12 − 8 = 4; 4 × 5 = 20.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 4, 9, 16, ___', NULL, '["20", "25", "21", "24"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Perfect squares: 1², 2², 3², 4², 5² = 25.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  2, 3, 5, 8, 13, ___', NULL, '["18", "19", "21", "20"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Fibonacci: each = sum of prior two. 8 + 13 = 21.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 5² − 3²  vs.  (B) (5−3)². Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, 'A: 25 − 9 = 16.  B: 2² = 4.  A is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'The average of five consecutive even numbers is 18. What is the largest?', NULL, '["20", "22", "24", "26"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Numbers centered on 18: 14,16,18,20,22. Largest = 22.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  5, 10, 15, 20, ___', NULL, '["22", "24", "25", "30"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Adding 5 each time: 20 + 5 = 25.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 2, 3, 4, ___', NULL, '["5", "6", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 0, 1, 'Adding 1 each time: 4 + 1 = 5.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  50, 45, 40, 35, ___', NULL, '["25", "28", "32", "30"]'::jsonb, 3, 1, 'Subtracting 5 each time: 35 − 5 = 30.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  3, 6, 9, 12, ___', NULL, '["14", "15", "16", "18"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Adding 3 each time (multiples of 3): 12 + 3 = 15.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  10, 20, 30, 40, ___', NULL, '["45", "48", "50", "60"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Adding 10 each time: 40 + 10 = 50.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  0, 5, 10, 15, ___', NULL, '["18", "20", "22", "25"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Adding 5 each time: 15 + 5 = 20.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  2, 4, 8, 16, ___', NULL, '["18", "24", "32", "64"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Each term doubles: 16 × 2 = 32.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  20, 18, 16, 14, ___', NULL, '["10", "11", "12", "13"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Subtracting 2 each time: 14 − 2 = 12.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 3, 5, 7, ___', NULL, '["8", "9", "10", "11"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Odd numbers, adding 2 each time: 7 + 2 = 9.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  4, 8, 12, 16, ___', NULL, '["18", "20", "22", "24"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Multiples of 4: 16 + 4 = 20.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  30, 25, 20, 15, ___', NULL, '["5", "8", "10", "12"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Subtracting 5 each time: 15 − 5 = 10.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  7, 14, 21, 28, ___', NULL, '["32", "35", "36", "42"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Multiples of 7: 28 + 7 = 35.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 1, 2, 3, ___', NULL, '["4", "5", "6", "7"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Each term is the sum of the two before it (Fibonacci start): 2 + 3 = 5.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  6, 12, 18, 24, ___', NULL, '["28", "30", "32", "36"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Multiples of 6: 24 + 6 = 30.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  9, 8, 7, 6, ___', NULL, '["4", "5", "3", "6"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Subtracting 1 each time: 6 − 1 = 5.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  0, 2, 4, 6, ___', NULL, '["7", "8", "9", "10"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'Even numbers: 6 + 2 = 8.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  40, 30, 20, 10, ___', NULL, '["0", "5", "2", "8"]'::jsonb, 0, 1, 'Subtracting 10 each time: 10 − 10 = 0.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  11, 22, 33, 44, ___', NULL, '["48", "50", "55", "66"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Multiples of 11: 44 + 11 = 55.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 4, 7, 10, ___', NULL, '["11", "12", "13", "14"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Adding 3 each time: 10 + 3 = 13.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  8, 16, 24, 32, ___', NULL, '["36", "38", "40", "48"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'Multiples of 8: 32 + 8 = 40.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is increased by 7 to give 15. What is the number?', NULL, '["6", "7", "8", "9"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '15 − 7 = 8.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is divided by 4 to give 5. What is the number?', NULL, '["16", "20", "24", "25"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '5 × 4 = 20.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is doubled to give 18. What is the number?', NULL, '["7", "8", "9", "10"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '18 ÷ 2 = 9.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is reduced by 12 to give 8. What is the number?', NULL, '["18", "20", "22", "24"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '8 + 12 = 20.'),
('quantitative', 'A number multiplied by 6 gives 42. What is the number?', NULL, '["5", "6", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '42 ÷ 6 = 7.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is tripled to give 27. What is the number?', NULL, '["7", "8", "9", "10"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '27 ÷ 3 = 9.'),
('quantitative', 'A number plus 15 equals 30. What is the number?', NULL, '["12", "13", "14", "15"]'::jsonb, 3, 1, '30 − 15 = 15.'),
('quantitative', 'A number divided by 9 gives 3. What is the number?', NULL, '["24", "27", "30", "33"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '3 × 9 = 27.'),
('quantitative', 'A number multiplied by 4 gives 36. What is the number?', NULL, '["7", "8", "9", "10"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '36 ÷ 4 = 9.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is decreased by 5 to give 11. What is the number?', NULL, '["14", "15", "16", "17"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '11 + 5 = 16.'),
('quantitative', 'A number multiplied by 8 gives 56. What is the number?', NULL, '["5", "6", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '56 ÷ 8 = 7.'),
('quantitative', 'A number is cut in half to give 13. What is the number?', NULL, '["24", "25", "26", "28"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '13 × 2 = 26.'),
('quantitative', 'A number plus 21 equals 50. What is the number?', NULL, '["27", "28", "29", "30"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '50 − 21 = 29.'),
('quantitative', 'A number multiplied by 7 gives 49. What is the number?', NULL, '["5", "6", "7", "8"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '49 ÷ 7 = 7.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 1/2  vs.  (B) 1/3. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 0, 1, '1/2 = 0.5; 1/3 ≈ 0.333. A is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 8 × 3  vs.  (B) 6 × 4. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'A: 8 × 3 = 24. B: 6 × 4 = 24. They are equal.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 15 − 6  vs.  (B) 4 + 5. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'A: 15 − 6 = 9. B: 4 + 5 = 9. Equal.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 2/5  vs.  (B) 3/10. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 0, 1, '2/5 = 4/10 = 0.4; 3/10 = 0.3. A is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 20 ÷ 4  vs.  (B) 3 × 2. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A: 20 ÷ 4 = 5. B: 3 × 2 = 6. B is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 7 + 4  vs.  (B) 3 × 4. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A: 7 + 4 = 11. B: 3 × 4 = 12. B is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Examine: (A) 3/4  vs.  (B) 6/8. Which is greater?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, '6/8 simplifies to 3/4. They are equal.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a rectangle with length 6 and width 4. Shape B: a rectangle with length 5 and width 5. Which has the greater area?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A: 6 × 4 = 24. B: 5 × 5 = 25. B is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a rectangle with length 8 and width 3. Shape B: a rectangle with length 6 and width 4. Which has the greater area?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'A: 8 × 3 = 24. B: 6 × 4 = 24. They are equal.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a rectangle with length 5 and width 3. Shape B: a rectangle with length 4 and width 4. Which has the greater perimeter?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'A: 2(5+3) = 16. B: 2(4+4) = 16. Equal.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a rectangle with length 10 and width 2. Shape B: a rectangle with length 7 and width 3. Which has the greater area?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A: 10 × 2 = 20. B: 7 × 3 = 21. B is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a square with side 4. Shape B: a rectangle with length 6 and width 3. Which has the greater perimeter?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A: 4 × 4 = 16. B: 2(6+3) = 18. B is greater.'),
('quantitative', 'Shape A: a rectangle with length 9 and width 2. Shape B: a rectangle with length 3 and width 6. Which has the greater area?', NULL, '["A is greater", "B is greater", "Equal", "Cannot determine"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'A: 9 × 2 = 18. B: 3 × 6 = 18. Equal.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  2, 6, 18, 54, ___', NULL, '["108", "144", "162", "216"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Each term is multiplied by 3: 54 × 3 = 162.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 2, 4, 7, 11, ___', NULL, '["14", "15", "16", "18"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Differences are +1, +2, +3, +4, so next difference is +5: 11 + 5 = 16.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  5, 15, 45, 135, ___', NULL, '["270", "375", "400", "405"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Each term multiplied by 3: 135 × 3 = 405.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  2, 5, 10, 17, 26, ___', NULL, '["35", "36", "37", "38"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Differences: +3, +5, +7, +9, +11. Next: 26 + 11 = 37.'),
('quantitative', 'What number comes next?  1, 3, 7, 15, 31, ___', NULL, '["47", "55", "62", "63"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Each term = previous × 2 + 1: 31 × 2 + 1 = 63.'),
