-- Sentence revision for concision (5)
,('language', 'Which revision best improves this sentence? "She was absent due to the fact that she was ill."', NULL, '["She was absent, due to the fact that, she was ill.", "She was absent because she was ill.", "Due to the fact that she was ill, she was absent.", "She was absent, due to her illness, which she had."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '"Due to the fact that" is a wordy phrase; "because" expresses the same cause-and-effect relationship in a single word.')
,('language', 'Which revision best improves this sentence? "At this point in time, we are unable to make a decision."', NULL, '["At this point in time now, we are unable to decide.", "Currently, we are unable to make a decision.", "At this point, in time, we cannot make a decision.", "At this point in time, a decision cannot be made by us."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '"At this point in time" is redundant; "currently" or "now" conveys the same meaning in one word.')
,('language', 'Which revision best improves this sentence? "In spite of the fact that it rained, the game continued."', NULL, '["In spite of the fact that it rained, the game went on continuing.", "Despite it rained, the game continued.", "Although it rained, the game continued.", "In spite of the rain fact, the game continued."]'::jsonb, 2, 2, '"In spite of the fact that" is wordy; "although" expresses the same concession in one word.')
,('language', 'Which revision best improves this sentence? "The reason why she failed is because she did not study."', NULL, '["The reason why she failed is that she did not study.", "She failed is because she did not study.", "She failed because she did not study.", "The reason she failed is due to the fact that she did not study."]'::jsonb, 2, 3, '"The reason why...is because" is doubly redundant. The cleanest fix removes both unnecessary phrases: "She failed because she did not study."')
,('language', 'Which revision best improves this sentence? "We need to review each and every application carefully."', NULL, '["We need to review every each application carefully.", "We need to carefully review each application.", "Each and every application must be reviewed by us carefully.", "We need to review each and every application with care and attention."]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '"Each and every" is redundant — "each" alone is sufficient. Moving the adverb closer to the verb also improves flow.')
-- Logical sentence ordering (5)
,('language', 'Sentences 1–4 appear in scrambled order. Which arrangement makes the most logical paragraph? 1. Attach the roof pieces at an angle so rainwater runs off. 2. Gather your wood, nails, and a hammer before you begin. 3. Finally, hang the finished birdhouse from a tree branch at least six feet off the ground. 4. Nail the four walls together, making sure the front piece has a small round entrance hole.', NULL, '["1, 2, 3, 4", "2, 4, 1, 3", "3, 1, 4, 2", "4, 2, 1, 3"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Logical construction order: gather materials (2), build walls (4), attach roof (1), then hang the finished product (3).')
,('language', 'Sentences 1–4 appear in scrambled order. Which arrangement makes the most logical paragraph? 1. This gravitational pull causes water on the side of Earth nearest the Moon to bulge outward. 2. Because of Earth''s rotation, most coastal locations experience two high tides and two low tides each day. 3. Tides are the periodic rise and fall of sea levels caused mainly by the Moon''s gravity. 4. At the same time, the opposite side of Earth bulges outward due to inertia, creating a second high tide.', NULL, '["1, 3, 4, 2", "3, 4, 1, 2", "3, 1, 4, 2", "2, 3, 1, 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Introduce the topic (3), explain the near-side bulge (1), explain the far-side bulge (4), then describe the daily pattern that results (2).')
,('language', 'Sentences 1–4 appear in scrambled order. Which arrangement makes the most logical paragraph? 1. Next, identify expenses you can reduce, such as dining out or subscription services. 2. With consistent effort, even small savings add up to a significant amount over time. 3. The first step to saving money is tracking exactly how much you spend each month. 4. Once you have cut costs, deposit the extra money into a dedicated savings account each payday.', NULL, '["1, 3, 2, 4", "3, 2, 1, 4", "2, 4, 3, 1", "3, 1, 4, 2"]'::jsonb, 3, 2, 'Track spending first (3), identify cuts (1), deposit savings (4), then observe the long-term result (2).')
,('language', 'Sentences 1–4 appear in scrambled order. Which arrangement makes the most logical paragraph? 1. Over centuries, it was extended and reinforced by successive dynasties, eventually stretching thousands of miles. 2. However, historians now believe it was never a single continuous wall but a series of connected fortifications. 3. The Great Wall of China was originally constructed to defend Chinese territory against northern invasions. 4. Despite its fame, the wall was not always effective — raiders frequently found ways around or through it.', NULL, '["3, 1, 2, 4", "1, 3, 4, 2", "3, 2, 4, 1", "2, 3, 1, 4"]'::jsonb, 0, 3, 'State the original purpose (3), show how it grew (1), clarify a common misconception (2), then acknowledge its limits (4).')
,('language', 'Sentences 1–4 appear in scrambled order. Which arrangement makes the most logical paragraph? 1. As warm, moist air rises, it cools, causing water vapor to condense into clouds. 2. Water on Earth''s surface evaporates when heated by the sun, turning from liquid into vapor. 3. This cycle of evaporation, condensation, and precipitation keeps Earth''s water supply constantly moving. 4. When enough water collects in clouds, it falls back to Earth as rain, snow, or sleet.', NULL, '["1, 4, 2, 3", "2, 1, 4, 3", "3, 2, 1, 4", "4, 1, 2, 3"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Evaporation (2) → condensation into clouds (1) → precipitation (4) → summarize the cycle (3).')
-- Sentence that does not belong (5)
,('language', 'Read the following paragraph. Which sentence does NOT belong? (1) Honeybees live in highly organized colonies that can contain up to 60,000 workers. (2) Each worker bee has a specific role — some gather nectar, others protect the hive, and some feed the young. (3) Wasps, unlike bees, do not produce honey and can sting multiple times. (4) The queen bee''s sole function is to lay eggs, sometimes thousands per day.', NULL, '["Sentence 1", "Sentence 2", "Sentence 3", "Sentence 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Sentences 1, 2, and 4 focus on honeybee colony structure and roles. Sentence 3 shifts to wasps — a related but different insect — and disrupts the paragraph''s unity.')
,('language', 'Read the following paragraph. Which sentence does NOT belong? (1) Thomas Edison held over a thousand patents, making him one of the most prolific inventors in history. (2) His invention of the phonograph allowed recorded sound to be played back for the first time. (3) Alexander Graham Bell, Edison''s contemporary, invented the telephone in 1876. (4) Edison also developed a practical electric light bulb and systems to distribute electricity to homes.', NULL, '["Sentence 1", "Sentence 2", "Sentence 3", "Sentence 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Sentences 1, 2, and 4 all describe Edison''s specific inventions. Sentence 3 introduces a different inventor (Bell) and breaks the paragraph''s focus on Edison.')
,('language', 'Read the following paragraph. Which sentence does NOT belong? (1) Photosynthesis is the process by which plants use sunlight to convert carbon dioxide and water into glucose. (2) This glucose provides plants with the energy they need to grow, flower, and reproduce. (3) Most plants grow better in well-drained soil with a neutral pH level. (4) As a byproduct of photosynthesis, plants release oxygen, which animals and humans need to breathe.', NULL, '["Sentence 1", "Sentence 2", "Sentence 3", "Sentence 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The paragraph explains how photosynthesis works and why it matters. Sentence 3 is about soil conditions — related to plant health, but unrelated to photosynthesis — and does not belong.')
,('language', 'Read the following paragraph. Which sentence does NOT belong? (1) The Amazon rainforest covers over 5.5 million square kilometers and is home to extraordinary biodiversity. (2) Scientists estimate that one in ten known species on Earth lives in the Amazon. (3) The Congo Basin in Africa is the world''s second-largest tropical rainforest. (4) Deforestation threatens this biodiversity, as thousands of acres of Amazon forest are lost each year.', NULL, '["Sentence 1", "Sentence 2", "Sentence 3", "Sentence 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The paragraph focuses on the Amazon''s biodiversity and the threat of deforestation. Sentence 3 introduces a different rainforest on a different continent and breaks the paragraph''s unity.')
,('language', 'Read the following paragraph. Which sentence does NOT belong? (1) The immune system is the body''s defense network against viruses, bacteria, and other harmful invaders. (2) White blood cells identify foreign substances and launch attacks to neutralize them. (3) The digestive system processes food into nutrients the body can absorb. (4) After an infection, the immune system retains a memory of the invader, making future responses faster.', NULL, '["Sentence 1", "Sentence 2", "Sentence 3", "Sentence 4"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'Sentences 1, 2, and 4 all describe how the immune system works. Sentence 3 is about the digestive system — a different body system — and does not belong.')
-- Transition words (5)
,('language', 'Which transition word or phrase best completes this sentence? "Mia trained for months; _____, she qualified for the state championship."', NULL, '["however", "nevertheless", "consequently", "in contrast"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, '"Consequently" signals a cause-and-effect relationship — the training caused the qualification. "However" and "nevertheless" signal contrast, which does not fit here.')
,('language', 'Which transition word or phrase best completes this sentence? "The original data appeared flawed; _____, the team collected new samples before publishing."', NULL, '["consequently", "however", "in addition", "meanwhile"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, '"Consequently" shows that the flawed data caused the team to collect new samples. "However" signals contrast; "in addition" signals addition; neither fits a cause-effect relationship.')
,('language', 'Which transition word or phrase best completes this sentence? "The candidate had strong qualifications; _____, she had never managed a team of more than five people."', NULL, '["therefore", "furthermore", "however", "in addition"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, '"However" signals contrast — the strong qualifications on one hand, and the limited management experience on the other. "Therefore" and "furthermore" signal result or addition, not contrast.')
,('language', 'Which transition word or phrase best completes this sentence? "Regular exercise improves cardiovascular health; _____, it reduces the risk of type 2 diabetes."', NULL, '["nevertheless", "moreover", "although", "consequently"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, '"Moreover" (or "furthermore") adds a second benefit to the first. "Nevertheless" signals concession; "although" signals contrast; neither fits when both clauses state positive outcomes.')
,('language', 'Which transition word or phrase best completes this sentence? "_____ the weather forecast predicted clear skies, the hiking group packed rain gear just in case."', NULL, '["Therefore", "Furthermore", "Although", "As a result"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, '"Although" introduces a concession — despite the sunny forecast, they prepared for rain anyway. "Therefore" and "As a result" signal cause-and-effect, which reverses the logical relationship.')
