,('reading', 'What is the PRIMARY reason deep-sea creatures produce bioluminescence, according to the passage?', 'In the pitch-black depths of the ocean, sunlight cannot reach, yet life thrives in spectacular fashion. Many deep-sea creatures produce their own light through a chemical process called bioluminescence. This glow serves several purposes: some fish use it to lure prey closer, while others flash patterns to attract mates or confuse predators. The anglerfish, for example, dangles a glowing lure above its mouth to draw in unsuspecting smaller fish. Scientists believe bioluminescence evolved independently in dozens of different marine species, making it one of nature''s most remarkable repeated inventions.', '["To help them see in the dark", "To serve multiple survival purposes such as luring prey and attracting mates", "To warm the cold ocean water around them", "To communicate with scientists on the surface"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage lists several purposes — luring prey, attracting mates, confusing predators — so the best answer captures that bioluminescence serves multiple survival functions.')

,('reading', 'What does the word "lure" mean as used in the passage about bioluminescence?', 'In the pitch-black depths of the ocean, sunlight cannot reach, yet life thrives in spectacular fashion. Many deep-sea creatures produce their own light through a chemical process called bioluminescence. This glow serves several purposes: some fish use it to lure prey closer, while others flash patterns to attract mates or confuse predators. The anglerfish, for example, dangles a glowing lure above its mouth to draw in unsuspecting smaller fish. Scientists believe bioluminescence evolved independently in dozens of different marine species, making it one of nature''s most remarkable repeated inventions.', '["A type of glowing chemical", "Something used to attract or draw in an animal", "A deep-sea predator", "The process of producing light"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'In context, "lure" refers to the dangling light that draws smaller fish toward the anglerfish — it is used as bait to attract prey.')

,('reading', 'Which conclusion can be drawn from the fact that bioluminescence "evolved independently in dozens of different marine species"?', 'In the pitch-black depths of the ocean, sunlight cannot reach, yet life thrives in spectacular fashion. Many deep-sea creatures produce their own light through a chemical process called bioluminescence. This glow serves several purposes: some fish use it to lure prey closer, while others flash patterns to attract mates or confuse predators. The anglerfish, for example, dangles a glowing lure above its mouth to draw in unsuspecting smaller fish. Scientists believe bioluminescence evolved independently in dozens of different marine species, making it one of nature''s most remarkable repeated inventions.', '["All deep-sea creatures share a common ancestor", "Producing light must provide a strong survival advantage", "Scientists invented bioluminescence through genetic engineering", "Only anglerfish are capable of producing light"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'If so many unrelated species evolved the same trait independently, it strongly suggests that trait gives a survival benefit. The passage itself calls it a "remarkable repeated invention," hinting at this idea.')

,('reading', 'What is this passage mainly about?', 'In the pitch-black depths of the ocean, sunlight cannot reach, yet life thrives in spectacular fashion. Many deep-sea creatures produce their own light through a chemical process called bioluminescence. This glow serves several purposes: some fish use it to lure prey closer, while others flash patterns to attract mates or confuse predators. The anglerfish, for example, dangles a glowing lure above its mouth to draw in unsuspecting smaller fish. Scientists believe bioluminescence evolved independently in dozens of different marine species, making it one of nature''s most remarkable repeated inventions.', '["The diet of the anglerfish", "How and why deep-sea creatures produce their own light", "Why the ocean depths are completely dark", "The history of marine biology research"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage introduces bioluminescence, explains the process, and describes its multiple purposes — making option B the best summary of the main idea.')

,('reading', 'Why does the author mention the anglerfish specifically?', 'In the pitch-black depths of the ocean, sunlight cannot reach, yet life thrives in spectacular fashion. Many deep-sea creatures produce their own light through a chemical process called bioluminescence. This glow serves several purposes: some fish use it to lure prey closer, while others flash patterns to attract mates or confuse predators. The anglerfish, for example, dangles a glowing lure above its mouth to draw in unsuspecting smaller fish. Scientists believe bioluminescence evolved independently in dozens of different marine species, making it one of nature''s most remarkable repeated inventions.', '["To show that anglerfish are the most dangerous ocean creatures", "To provide a specific, concrete example of bioluminescence used for hunting", "To explain how bioluminescence was first discovered", "To argue that all fish should be studied more carefully"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The author uses the anglerfish as a clear, specific example right after stating that some fish use light to lure prey — a classic author''s technique of illustrating a general claim with a concrete case.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, where did sign language first develop in an organized way?', 'Sign language is a complete, complex language expressed through hand movements, facial expressions, and body posture rather than spoken words. Although deaf communities around the world have always developed informal signing systems, the first formal sign language school was established in Paris in 1760 by Abbé de l''Épée. His school later influenced American Sign Language (ASL) when a French teacher named Laurent Clerc traveled to the United States in 1817 to help found the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut. Today, linguists recognize that sign languages are fully independent languages with their own grammar and syntax, not simply coded versions of spoken language.', '["Hartford, Connecticut", "Paris, France", "Throughout ancient Greece", "Washington, D.C."]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage directly states that the first formal sign language school was established in Paris in 1760.')

,('reading', 'What does the word "syntax" most likely mean as used in the passage about sign language?', 'Sign language is a complete, complex language expressed through hand movements, facial expressions, and body posture rather than spoken words. Although deaf communities around the world have always developed informal signing systems, the first formal sign language school was established in Paris in 1760 by Abbé de l''Épée. His school later influenced American Sign Language (ASL) when a French teacher named Laurent Clerc traveled to the United States in 1817 to help found the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut. Today, linguists recognize that sign languages are fully independent languages with their own grammar and syntax, not simply coded versions of spoken language.', '["A list of hand movements", "The rules for arranging words or signs into sentences", "A type of hearing device", "The historical study of language"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Syntax refers to the rules that govern sentence structure in a language. The passage pairs "grammar and syntax" together, signaling that both are structural features of language.')

,('reading', 'What inference can be made about ASL based on information in the passage?', 'Sign language is a complete, complex language expressed through hand movements, facial expressions, and body posture rather than spoken words. Although deaf communities around the world have always developed informal signing systems, the first formal sign language school was established in Paris in 1760 by Abbé de l''Épée. His school later influenced American Sign Language (ASL) when a French teacher named Laurent Clerc traveled to the United States in 1817 to help found the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut. Today, linguists recognize that sign languages are fully independent languages with their own grammar and syntax, not simply coded versions of spoken language.', '["ASL and French Sign Language share some historical roots", "ASL was invented entirely without any European influence", "ASL is simpler than spoken English", "ASL can only be understood by people who are completely deaf"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'Since Laurent Clerc was French and helped bring sign language to America after training in the Paris school, it is reasonable to infer that ASL has roots connected to French Sign Language.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage about sign language?', 'Sign language is a complete, complex language expressed through hand movements, facial expressions, and body posture rather than spoken words. Although deaf communities around the world have always developed informal signing systems, the first formal sign language school was established in Paris in 1760 by Abbé de l''Épée. His school later influenced American Sign Language (ASL) when a French teacher named Laurent Clerc traveled to the United States in 1817 to help found the American School for the Deaf in Hartford, Connecticut. Today, linguists recognize that sign languages are fully independent languages with their own grammar and syntax, not simply coded versions of spoken language.', '["Laurent Clerc was the most important figure in the history of language", "Sign languages are real, complete languages with a formal history of development", "Deaf people communicate less effectively than hearing people", "All sign languages around the world are essentially the same"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage emphasizes that sign languages are full, independent languages with formal grammar and traces their organized development — making option B the best summary.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what drives the water cycle?', 'Water is constantly moving through Earth''s systems in a never-ending process called the water cycle. Energy from the sun causes water in oceans, lakes, and rivers to evaporate, turning liquid water into water vapor that rises into the atmosphere. As the vapor rises, it cools and condenses into tiny droplets, forming clouds. When enough droplets combine, precipitation falls as rain or snow. This water then flows into rivers, soaks into the ground, or collects in lakes — and the cycle begins again. The water cycle not only replenishes freshwater supplies but also helps regulate temperature and drive weather patterns around the globe.', '["The rotation of the Earth", "Energy from the sun", "The gravitational pull of the moon", "Wind patterns alone"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explicitly states that "energy from the sun" causes water to evaporate, which is the starting point of the cycle.')

,('reading', 'What does "condenses" mean as used in the passage about the water cycle?', 'Water is constantly moving through Earth''s systems in a never-ending process called the water cycle. Energy from the sun causes water in oceans, lakes, and rivers to evaporate, turning liquid water into water vapor that rises into the atmosphere. As the vapor rises, it cools and condenses into tiny droplets, forming clouds. When enough droplets combine, precipitation falls as rain or snow. This water then flows into rivers, soaks into the ground, or collects in lakes — and the cycle begins again. The water cycle not only replenishes freshwater supplies but also helps regulate temperature and drive weather patterns around the globe.', '["Evaporates into the air", "Changes from gas back into liquid", "Freezes into ice crystals", "Sinks into the ground"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage describes vapor rising, cooling, and condensing into tiny droplets — showing that condensation is the change from vapor (gas) back into liquid water.')

