,('reading', 'What is the passage''s main purpose?', 'Water is constantly moving through Earth''s systems in a never-ending process called the water cycle. Energy from the sun causes water in oceans, lakes, and rivers to evaporate, turning liquid water into water vapor that rises into the atmosphere. As the vapor rises, it cools and condenses into tiny droplets, forming clouds. When enough droplets combine, precipitation falls as rain or snow. This water then flows into rivers, soaks into the ground, or collects in lakes — and the cycle begins again. The water cycle not only replenishes freshwater supplies but also helps regulate temperature and drive weather patterns around the globe.', '["To argue that humans must protect the water supply", "To explain the continuous process by which water moves through Earth''s systems", "To describe how clouds are formed in detail", "To compare different forms of precipitation"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage traces water through each stage of the cycle and explains its larger role — explaining the overall process is its main purpose.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what was cuneiform first used to record?', 'More than 5,000 years ago, people in ancient Mesopotamia — the region between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers — developed one of the world''s earliest writing systems, known as cuneiform. Early scribes pressed a wedge-shaped reed stylus into soft clay tablets to create marks representing words and numbers. At first, cuneiform was used almost exclusively to keep economic records: tracking grain, livestock, and trade goods. Over centuries, the system expanded to record laws, stories, religious texts, and royal decrees. The famous Epic of Gilgamesh, one of the oldest surviving works of literature, was preserved on cuneiform tablets and tells the story of a legendary Mesopotamian king.', '["Laws and royal decrees", "Religious ceremonies", "Economic records such as grain and livestock", "Epic poems and stories"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage states that cuneiform was first used "almost exclusively to keep economic records: tracking grain, livestock, and trade goods."')

