,('reading', 'According to the passage, how do vaccines teach the immune system to fight disease?', 'Vaccines work by training the immune system to recognize and defeat specific pathogens before a real infection occurs. When a vaccine is administered, it introduces a harmless version of a pathogen — such as a weakened or inactivated virus, or just a piece of its protein — into the body. The immune system detects this foreign material and produces antibodies, proteins designed to neutralize that specific threat. If the person later encounters the real pathogen, the immune system "remembers" it and responds rapidly, often stopping the disease before symptoms develop. This principle, called immunological memory, is what makes vaccination one of the most powerful tools in public health.', '["By introducing a full-strength dose of the disease", "By introducing a harmless form of the pathogen so the immune system learns to fight it", "By injecting antibodies directly from other people", "By strengthening the immune system through nutrition"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage directly explains that vaccines introduce "a harmless version of a pathogen" so the immune system can learn to recognize and fight it.')

