,('reading', 'According to the passage, what would most likely happen if a vaccinated person were exposed to the real pathogen?', 'Vaccines work by training the immune system to recognize and defeat specific pathogens before a real infection occurs. When a vaccine is administered, it introduces a harmless version of a pathogen — such as a weakened or inactivated virus, or just a piece of its protein — into the body. The immune system detects this foreign material and produces antibodies, proteins designed to neutralize that specific threat. If the person later encounters the real pathogen, the immune system "remembers" it and responds rapidly, often stopping the disease before symptoms develop. This principle, called immunological memory, is what makes vaccination one of the most powerful tools in public health.', '["They would become very ill because vaccines weaken the immune system", "Their immune system would respond quickly and likely prevent the disease", "They would need to receive another vaccine immediately", "Their body would produce no antibodies at all"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage states that upon re-exposure, the immune system "responds rapidly, often stopping the disease before symptoms develop" — option B accurately reflects this outcome.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, why are bees essential to many ecosystems?', 'Bees are among the most important animals on Earth, not because of their honey but because of their role as pollinators. As bees travel from flower to flower collecting nectar, they transfer pollen, enabling plants to reproduce. This process, called pollination, is essential for the production of fruits, vegetables, nuts, and seeds that countless species — including humans — depend on for food. Scientists estimate that roughly one-third of the food humans eat relies on pollination. Habitat loss, pesticide use, and disease have caused bee populations to decline sharply in recent decades, alarming ecologists who warn that the loss of bees could trigger widespread food shortages.', '["They produce honey that humans and animals eat", "They pollinate plants that produce food for many species", "They control insect populations by eating harmful pests", "They help spread seeds by carrying them in their legs"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explicitly states bees'' importance is their role as pollinators, enabling plant reproduction and food production — not their honey.')

