,('reading', 'According to the passage, what happens in the brain during sleep?', 'Sleep is far more than simply resting. While the body is still, the brain remains remarkably active, performing critical maintenance work. During deep sleep, the brain consolidates memories — transferring information from short-term to long-term storage. It also clears out waste products that build up during waking hours, including proteins linked to neurological diseases. During a phase called REM sleep, the brain processes emotions and may generate dreams. Sleep deprivation disrupts all of these processes, impairing memory, judgment, and emotional regulation. Scientists now understand that adequate sleep — typically seven to nine hours for teenagers — is not optional but essential for brain and body health.', '["The brain shuts down to save energy", "The brain consolidates memories, clears waste, and processes emotions", "The brain produces growth hormones only during waking hours", "The brain replays the day''s experiences in order"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage lists three things the brain does during sleep: consolidates memories, clears waste products, and processes emotions. Option B captures all three.')

