,('reading', 'According to the passage, where did jazz music first develop?', 'Jazz is a uniquely American art form that grew out of the vibrant African American communities of New Orleans in the late 1800s and early 1900s. It blends elements of African rhythmic traditions, blues, gospel, and European harmonic structures into an improvisational style unlike anything before it. Early jazz musicians played in venues called "juke joints" and at community celebrations, often creating music on the spot rather than reading from written scores. Jazz spread rapidly up the Mississippi River to Chicago and then to New York, where it flourished during the Harlem Renaissance. Today, jazz is recognized worldwide as one of America''s greatest cultural contributions.', '["Chicago, Illinois", "New York City", "New Orleans, Louisiana", "Memphis, Tennessee"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage directly states jazz "grew out of the vibrant African American communities of New Orleans."')

,('reading', 'What does "improvisational" most likely mean in the context of the passage about jazz?', 'Jazz is a uniquely American art form that grew out of the vibrant African American communities of New Orleans in the late 1800s and early 1900s. It blends elements of African rhythmic traditions, blues, gospel, and European harmonic structures into an improvisational style unlike anything before it. Early jazz musicians played in venues called "juke joints" and at community celebrations, often creating music on the spot rather than reading from written scores. Jazz spread rapidly up the Mississippi River to Chicago and then to New York, where it flourished during the Harlem Renaissance. Today, jazz is recognized worldwide as one of America''s greatest cultural contributions.', '["Based on strict written musical rules", "Created spontaneously in the moment rather than planned in advance", "Influenced by European classical music", "Performed only for large audiences"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage says musicians created music "on the spot rather than reading from written scores," which is exactly what improvisation means — making it up spontaneously.')

