,('reading', 'According to the passage, how does the eye detect different colors?', 'The human eye can distinguish millions of colors, but the actual process of color vision begins with specialized cells called cones, located in the retina at the back of the eye. There are three types of cones, each most sensitive to a different wavelength of light: one type responds mainly to red light, one to green, and one to blue. When light enters the eye, the cones detect these wavelengths and send electrical signals to the brain, which combines the signals to produce the full range of colors we perceive. People who are colorblind are typically missing one type of cone or have cones that do not function normally, causing them to confuse certain colors.', '["By measuring the brightness of incoming light", "Through three types of cone cells that each respond to a different wavelength of light", "Through rod cells that detect red, green, and blue light", "By measuring the speed at which light enters the eye"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explains that three types of cones — each sensitive to a different wavelength — detect color and send signals to the brain.')

,('reading', 'What does "wavelength" suggest about light in the context of this passage?', 'The human eye can distinguish millions of colors, but the actual process of color vision begins with specialized cells called cones, located in the retina at the back of the eye. There are three types of cones, each most sensitive to a different wavelength of light: one type responds mainly to red light, one to green, and one to blue. When light enters the eye, the cones detect these wavelengths and send electrical signals to the brain, which combines the signals to produce the full range of colors we perceive. People who are colorblind are typically missing one type of cone or have cones that do not function normally, causing them to confuse certain colors.', '["Light travels in waves of different sizes, and color is related to those differences", "Light is a solid particle that bounces off objects", "Wavelength refers to the brightness of a color", "Only visible light has a wavelength"]'::jsonb, 0, 2, 'The context shows that different wavelengths correspond to different colors (red, green, blue), suggesting that light travels in waves and that color is determined by the size or frequency of those waves.')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred about why colorblind people confuse certain colors?', 'The human eye can distinguish millions of colors, but the actual process of color vision begins with specialized cells called cones, located in the retina at the back of the eye. There are three types of cones, each most sensitive to a different wavelength of light: one type responds mainly to red light, one to green, and one to blue. When light enters the eye, the cones detect these wavelengths and send electrical signals to the brain, which combines the signals to produce the full range of colors we perceive. People who are colorblind are typically missing one type of cone or have cones that do not function normally, causing them to confuse certain colors.', '["Their brains are unable to process electrical signals", "Without a functioning cone type, their brain receives incomplete information about certain wavelengths", "They have too many cone cells, creating confusion", "They see the world in black and white only"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'Since each cone type detects a specific wavelength, a missing or broken cone type means the brain does not receive the signal for that color — making it impossible to distinguish colors that depend on that cone.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage?', 'The human eye can distinguish millions of colors, but the actual process of color vision begins with specialized cells called cones, located in the retina at the back of the eye. There are three types of cones, each most sensitive to a different wavelength of light: one type responds mainly to red light, one to green, and one to blue. When light enters the eye, the cones detect these wavelengths and send electrical signals to the brain, which combines the signals to produce the full range of colors we perceive. People who are colorblind are typically missing one type of cone or have cones that do not function normally, causing them to confuse certain colors.', '["The eye is the most complex organ in the human body", "Color vision works through three types of specialized cells that detect light wavelengths", "Colorblindness is a very common condition that affects everyone slightly", "The brain produces color without any input from the eyes"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage focuses on how the eye''s cone cells detect wavelengths to produce color vision, and uses colorblindness as an illustration. Option B captures the core explanation.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, who is credited with inventing the telephone?', 'The invention of the telephone in 1876 transformed human communication forever. Alexander Graham Bell, a Scottish-born inventor working in Boston, is credited with creating the first practical telephone and receiving the first patent for the device. Bell''s inspiration came partly from his work with deaf students and his interest in understanding how sound travels. His first successful telephone call was made to his assistant, Thomas Watson, with the now-famous words: "Mr. Watson — come here — I want to see you." Although other inventors were working on similar devices at the same time, Bell filed his patent just hours before a competing inventor, securing his place in history.', '["Thomas Watson", "A Scottish engineer in Glasgow", "Alexander Graham Bell", "An unnamed inventor who filed first"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage directly states "Alexander Graham Bell...is credited with creating the first practical telephone."')

,('reading', 'What does "patent" mean as used in the passage about the telephone?', 'The invention of the telephone in 1876 transformed human communication forever. Alexander Graham Bell, a Scottish-born inventor working in Boston, is credited with creating the first practical telephone and receiving the first patent for the device. Bell''s inspiration came partly from his work with deaf students and his interest in understanding how sound travels. His first successful telephone call was made to his assistant, Thomas Watson, with the now-famous words: "Mr. Watson — come here — I want to see you." Although other inventors were working on similar devices at the same time, Bell filed his patent just hours before a competing inventor, securing his place in history.', '["A financial prize for inventors", "An official legal document granting the inventor exclusive rights to their invention", "A scientific paper describing how the telephone works", "A government contract to build telephones"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'A patent is a legal document giving an inventor the exclusive right to their invention. The passage shows Bell filed for it to officially claim credit, which aligns with this definition.')

