,('reading', 'According to the passage, what causes earthquakes?', 'Earth''s outer layer is not a single solid shell but a patchwork of giant rocky slabs called tectonic plates. These plates fit together like pieces of a puzzle and move slowly — just centimeters per year — driven by heat rising from Earth''s interior. Where plates meet, tremendous forces build up over time. When the stress becomes too great, the plates suddenly slip or grind past one another, releasing energy in waves that shake the ground — an earthquake. Volcanoes also tend to form near plate boundaries, since magma can force its way to the surface along cracks between plates. Most of the world''s earthquakes and volcanoes occur along the "Ring of Fire," a zone encircling the Pacific Ocean.', '["The cooling of Earth''s core", "The sudden release of energy when tectonic plates slip or grind", "Pressure from underground rivers and caves", "Volcanic eruptions that shake surrounding rock"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage states directly: when stress becomes too great, plates "slip or grind past one another, releasing energy in waves that shake the ground — an earthquake."')

