,('reading', 'What can be inferred about why the "Ring of Fire" has so many earthquakes and volcanoes?', 'Earth''s outer layer is not a single solid shell but a patchwork of giant rocky slabs called tectonic plates. These plates fit together like pieces of a puzzle and move slowly — just centimeters per year — driven by heat rising from Earth''s interior. Where plates meet, tremendous forces build up over time. When the stress becomes too great, the plates suddenly slip or grind past one another, releasing energy in waves that shake the ground — an earthquake. Volcanoes also tend to form near plate boundaries, since magma can force its way to the surface along cracks between plates. Most of the world''s earthquakes and volcanoes occur along the "Ring of Fire," a zone encircling the Pacific Ocean.', '["The Pacific Ocean is unusually warm, heating the plates beneath it", "Several tectonic plate boundaries meet around the Pacific Ocean", "The Ring of Fire is made of different rock than other regions", "Earthquakes in one region trigger earthquakes across the Pacific"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The passage explains that earthquakes and volcanoes occur at plate boundaries. Since the Ring of Fire has "most of the world''s earthquakes and volcanoes," we can infer it has many plate boundaries converging around the Pacific.')

,('reading', 'What is this passage primarily about?', 'Earth''s outer layer is not a single solid shell but a patchwork of giant rocky slabs called tectonic plates. These plates fit together like pieces of a puzzle and move slowly — just centimeters per year — driven by heat rising from Earth''s interior. Where plates meet, tremendous forces build up over time. When the stress becomes too great, the plates suddenly slip or grind past one another, releasing energy in waves that shake the ground — an earthquake. Volcanoes also tend to form near plate boundaries, since magma can force its way to the surface along cracks between plates. Most of the world''s earthquakes and volcanoes occur along the "Ring of Fire," a zone encircling the Pacific Ocean.', '["How volcanoes form beneath the sea", "The composition of Earth''s inner core", "How tectonic plates move and cause earthquakes and volcanoes", "The history of earthquake measurement"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The passage explains plate tectonics — what plates are, how they move, and how that movement produces earthquakes and volcanoes. Option C is the most complete summary.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what is the final stage in the life of a massive star?', 'Stars are not permanent fixtures in the sky — they are born, live for millions or billions of years, and eventually die. A star begins as a cloud of gas and dust called a nebula. Gravity pulls this material together, and when the core grows hot enough, nuclear fusion ignites and a star is born. For most of its life, a star burns hydrogen fuel. When the hydrogen runs out, the star expands into a red giant. Small stars like our sun will eventually shed their outer layers and leave behind a dense core called a white dwarf. Massive stars, however, end dramatically: they collapse and explode in a violent supernova, sometimes leaving behind an incredibly dense remnant called a neutron star or even a black hole.', '["They slowly cool into a white dwarf", "They expand permanently into a red giant", "They collapse and explode in a supernova, possibly becoming a neutron star or black hole", "They break apart into smaller stars"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage directly states that massive stars "collapse and explode in a violent supernova, sometimes leaving behind...a neutron star or even a black hole."')

