,('reading', 'According to the passage, what was ARPANET?', 'The internet we use today grew from a much smaller network created in 1969 called ARPANET, funded by the United States Department of Defense. ARPANET connected computers at a handful of universities and research labs, allowing scientists to share data across long distances for the first time. Over the following decades, the network expanded and the rules governing how computers communicate — called protocols — were standardized. In 1991, scientist Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web, a system of linked pages that made the internet far easier for ordinary people to navigate. Today, billions of people use the internet daily for communication, commerce, education, and entertainment.', '["The first personal computer sold to the public", "An early government-funded computer network that was the predecessor to the internet", "A software program for browsing websites", "The organization that manages the internet today"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage directly describes ARPANET as a network "funded by the United States Department of Defense" that connected research institutions — the foundation of what became the internet.')

,('reading', 'What does "protocols" mean in the context of this passage?', 'The internet we use today grew from a much smaller network created in 1969 called ARPANET, funded by the United States Department of Defense. ARPANET connected computers at a handful of universities and research labs, allowing scientists to share data across long distances for the first time. Over the following decades, the network expanded and the rules governing how computers communicate — called protocols — were standardized. In 1991, scientist Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web, a system of linked pages that made the internet far easier for ordinary people to navigate. Today, billions of people use the internet daily for communication, commerce, education, and entertainment.', '["High-speed cables that connect computers", "The rules or standards that govern how computers communicate with each other", "Programs that protect computers from viruses", "A type of hardware used in early computers"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage defines protocols in context: "the rules governing how computers communicate." Option B restates this definition accurately.')

,('reading', 'Why did Tim Berners-Lee''s invention of the World Wide Web matter for ordinary people?', 'The internet we use today grew from a much smaller network created in 1969 called ARPANET, funded by the United States Department of Defense. ARPANET connected computers at a handful of universities and research labs, allowing scientists to share data across long distances for the first time. Over the following decades, the network expanded and the rules governing how computers communicate — called protocols — were standardized. In 1991, scientist Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web, a system of linked pages that made the internet far easier for ordinary people to navigate. Today, billions of people use the internet daily for communication, commerce, education, and entertainment.', '["It made the internet faster for scientists at universities", "It made the internet accessible and easy to navigate for people outside research labs", "It replaced ARPANET with a more secure system", "It reduced the cost of computers so more families could buy them"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage says the World Wide Web "made the internet far easier for ordinary people to navigate" — before this, the internet was mainly used by researchers. Option B correctly identifies the impact.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage?', 'The internet we use today grew from a much smaller network created in 1969 called ARPANET, funded by the United States Department of Defense. ARPANET connected computers at a handful of universities and research labs, allowing scientists to share data across long distances for the first time. Over the following decades, the network expanded and the rules governing how computers communicate — called protocols — were standardized. In 1991, scientist Tim Berners-Lee invented the World Wide Web, a system of linked pages that made the internet far easier for ordinary people to navigate. Today, billions of people use the internet daily for communication, commerce, education, and entertainment.', '["Tim Berners-Lee is the most important inventor in modern history", "The internet developed gradually from a small military research network into a global tool", "ARPANET was invented to help soldiers communicate during wartime", "The World Wide Web and the internet are exactly the same thing"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage traces the internet from ARPANET in 1969 to global use today — option B correctly captures this arc of gradual development.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, how do bats use echolocation to navigate?', 'Bats are nocturnal animals that navigate and hunt in total darkness using a biological sonar system called echolocation. A bat emits high-pitched sound pulses — far beyond the range of human hearing — that travel outward and bounce off objects in the environment. The returning echoes reach the bat''s large, highly sensitive ears, providing detailed information about the size, distance, shape, and even texture of nearby objects. This system is so precise that a bat can detect and catch a moth in complete darkness while avoiding obstacles thinner than a wire. Scientists have studied echolocation extensively, and insights from this research have contributed to the development of sonar and radar technology used by ships and aircraft.', '["By using their large eyes to see in very dim light", "By emitting sound pulses and interpreting the returning echoes", "By sensing vibrations through their wings", "By following the magnetic field of the Earth"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage directly describes echolocation: bats emit sound pulses that bounce off objects, and the returning echoes provide navigation information.')

,('reading', 'What does "nocturnal" mean as used in the passage about bats?', 'Bats are nocturnal animals that navigate and hunt in total darkness using a biological sonar system called echolocation. A bat emits high-pitched sound pulses — far beyond the range of human hearing — that travel outward and bounce off objects in the environment. The returning echoes reach the bat''s large, highly sensitive ears, providing detailed information about the size, distance, shape, and even texture of nearby objects. This system is so precise that a bat can detect and catch a moth in complete darkness while avoiding obstacles thinner than a wire. Scientists have studied echolocation extensively, and insights from this research have contributed to the development of sonar and radar technology used by ships and aircraft.', '["Active during daylight hours", "Active during the night", "Capable of seeing in the dark", "Able to survive without food for weeks"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '"Nocturnal" means active at night. The passage pairs "nocturnal" with navigating in "total darkness," confirming the nighttime meaning.')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred from the fact that bats can catch moths in complete darkness?', 'Bats are nocturnal animals that navigate and hunt in total darkness using a biological sonar system called echolocation. A bat emits high-pitched sound pulses — far beyond the range of human hearing — that travel outward and bounce off objects in the environment. The returning echoes reach the bat''s large, highly sensitive ears, providing detailed information about the size, distance, shape, and even texture of nearby objects. This system is so precise that a bat can detect and catch a moth in complete darkness while avoiding obstacles thinner than a wire. Scientists have studied echolocation extensively, and insights from this research have contributed to the development of sonar and radar technology used by ships and aircraft.', '["Bats have better eyesight than most other animals", "Echolocation provides bats with extremely precise spatial information", "Moths are easy to catch because they fly slowly", "Bats can only hunt when conditions are perfectly quiet"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Catching a small, fast-moving moth in complete darkness requires highly precise spatial awareness — this implies echolocation provides detailed and accurate information about the surroundings.')

,('reading', 'Why does the author mention sonar and radar technology at the end of the passage?', 'Bats are nocturnal animals that navigate and hunt in total darkness using a biological sonar system called echolocation. A bat emits high-pitched sound pulses — far beyond the range of human hearing — that travel outward and bounce off objects in the environment. The returning echoes reach the bat''s large, highly sensitive ears, providing detailed information about the size, distance, shape, and even texture of nearby objects. This system is so precise that a bat can detect and catch a moth in complete darkness while avoiding obstacles thinner than a wire. Scientists have studied echolocation extensively, and insights from this research have contributed to the development of sonar and radar technology used by ships and aircraft.', '["To suggest that bats are more intelligent than machines", "To show that studying bats has had real-world benefits for human technology", "To argue that ships and aircraft should use bats instead of sonar", "To explain why scientists prefer bats to other nocturnal animals"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The author includes this detail to show that bat research has practical value — it inspired technologies we use today. This broadens the relevance of the passage beyond just bats.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, how does the color of an object affect how we perceive it?', 'Color is not just a feature of the physical world — it is a creation of the mind. When light strikes an object, the object absorbs some wavelengths and reflects others. The reflected wavelengths reach our eyes and are interpreted by the brain as color. Because the brain also uses context to make sense of color, two identical colors can appear different depending on what surrounds them. This is why a gray square looks darker when placed on a white background than when placed on a black one. Marketers use this knowledge to influence behavior: studies show that red can increase excitement and urgency, blue is associated with trust and calm, and yellow draws attention quickly.', '["Objects produce their own color through internal chemistry", "Objects reflect certain wavelengths of light, which the brain interprets as color", "The brain ignores color and focuses on shape instead", "Color perception is the same for all people in all situations"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explains that objects absorb some wavelengths and reflect others, and the reflected light is interpreted by the brain as color.')

,('reading', 'What does "context" mean as used in the passage about color perception?', 'Color is not just a feature of the physical world — it is a creation of the mind. When light strikes an object, the object absorbs some wavelengths and reflects others. The reflected wavelengths reach our eyes and are interpreted by the brain as color. Because the brain also uses context to make sense of color, two identical colors can appear different depending on what surrounds them. This is why a gray square looks darker when placed on a white background than when placed on a black one. Marketers use this knowledge to influence behavior: studies show that red can increase excitement and urgency, blue is associated with trust and calm, and yellow draws attention quickly.', '["The wavelength of light reflected by an object", "The surrounding environment that influences how something is perceived", "The part of the brain responsible for color vision", "The history of how humans learned about color"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage shows that surrounding colors change how we perceive a color — "context" means the surrounding information the brain uses to interpret what it sees.')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred about why marketers choose specific colors for products and advertisements?', 'Color is not just a feature of the physical world — it is a creation of the mind. When light strikes an object, the object absorbs some wavelengths and reflects others. The reflected wavelengths reach our eyes and are interpreted by the brain as color. Because the brain also uses context to make sense of color, two identical colors can appear different depending on what surrounds them. This is why a gray square looks darker when placed on a white background than when placed on a black one. Marketers use this knowledge to influence behavior: studies show that red can increase excitement and urgency, blue is associated with trust and calm, and yellow draws attention quickly.', '["They choose colors purely for artistic reasons", "They use color strategically to trigger specific emotional responses in consumers", "They always choose the brightest colors to attract attention", "They rely on customers'' favorite colors rather than psychological research"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The passage describes how specific colors trigger specific feelings (urgency, trust, attention) — marketers apply this psychology to influence how consumers feel about products.')

,('reading', 'What is the passage mainly about?', 'Color is not just a feature of the physical world — it is a creation of the mind. When light strikes an object, the object absorbs some wavelengths and reflects others. The reflected wavelengths reach our eyes and are interpreted by the brain as color. Because the brain also uses context to make sense of color, two identical colors can appear different depending on what surrounds them. This is why a gray square looks darker when placed on a white background than when placed on a black one. Marketers use this knowledge to influence behavior: studies show that red can increase excitement and urgency, blue is associated with trust and calm, and yellow draws attention quickly.', '["Why red is the most powerful color in marketing", "How the brain interprets color and how color can influence perception and behavior", "The physical properties of light and wavelengths", "Why all people perceive color differently"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage covers both the science of how color is perceived and the psychological effects of color on behavior — option B captures both aspects.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what tools did Pacific Islander navigators use to find their way?', 'Long before the invention of the compass or GPS, indigenous navigators of the Pacific Islands crossed thousands of miles of open ocean using only natural cues. By reading the stars — particularly the position and movement of key constellations — they could determine latitude and direction. They also studied ocean swells, which move in predictable patterns from distant wind sources, and used the feel of wave motion beneath their canoes to stay on course. The color of the water, cloud formations, and even the behavior of birds indicated the presence of nearby islands. This sophisticated system of wayfinding, passed down through oral tradition and practice, enabled Polynesian peoples to settle islands across a vast region of the Pacific.', '["Compasses and early maps drawn on animal skins", "Stars, ocean swells, wave motion, water color, clouds, and birds", "Radio signals and ocean charts", "Magnetic rocks and tidal patterns"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage lists stars, ocean swells, wave motion, water color, cloud formations, and bird behavior as the tools Pacific navigators used.')

,('reading', 'What does "wayfinding" most likely mean in this passage?', 'Long before the invention of the compass or GPS, indigenous navigators of the Pacific Islands crossed thousands of miles of open ocean using only natural cues. By reading the stars — particularly the position and movement of key constellations — they could determine latitude and direction. They also studied ocean swells, which move in predictable patterns from distant wind sources, and used the feel of wave motion beneath their canoes to stay on course. The color of the water, cloud formations, and even the behavior of birds indicated the presence of nearby islands. This sophisticated system of wayfinding, passed down through oral tradition and practice, enabled Polynesian peoples to settle islands across a vast region of the Pacific.', '["Building boats strong enough to cross oceans", "The skill of navigating and finding one''s route using available information", "Reading weather patterns to predict storms", "Swimming from island to island"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, '"Wayfinding" is described as a sophisticated navigation system — in context it means the practice of finding one''s way, especially using natural signs.')

,('reading', 'What does the phrase "passed down through oral tradition" suggest about how this knowledge was preserved?', 'Long before the invention of the compass or GPS, indigenous navigators of the Pacific Islands crossed thousands of miles of open ocean using only natural cues. By reading the stars — particularly the position and movement of key constellations — they could determine latitude and direction. They also studied ocean swells, which move in predictable patterns from distant wind sources, and used the feel of wave motion beneath their canoes to stay on course. The color of the water, cloud formations, and even the behavior of birds indicated the presence of nearby islands. This sophisticated system of wayfinding, passed down through oral tradition and practice, enabled Polynesian peoples to settle islands across a vast region of the Pacific.', '["The knowledge was written in books stored in temples", "The knowledge was spoken and memorized, not written down", "The knowledge was kept secret and shared only with royalty", "The knowledge was learned from European sailors"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'Oral tradition means knowledge is spoken aloud and memorized rather than recorded in writing — this is how the navigation knowledge survived across generations.')

,('reading', 'What is the passage mainly about?', 'Long before the invention of the compass or GPS, indigenous navigators of the Pacific Islands crossed thousands of miles of open ocean using only natural cues. By reading the stars — particularly the position and movement of key constellations — they could determine latitude and direction. They also studied ocean swells, which move in predictable patterns from distant wind sources, and used the feel of wave motion beneath their canoes to stay on course. The color of the water, cloud formations, and even the behavior of birds indicated the presence of nearby islands. This sophisticated system of wayfinding, passed down through oral tradition and practice, enabled Polynesian peoples to settle islands across a vast region of the Pacific.', '["Why the Pacific Ocean is the most difficult ocean to cross", "The sophisticated navigation methods used by indigenous Pacific Islander peoples", "The history of the compass and its importance to sailors", "How Polynesian peoples first discovered the Pacific Islands"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage focuses on describing the natural navigation techniques of Pacific Islander peoples and acknowledging their sophistication — option B captures the subject and emphasis.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what happens to the price of a product when demand increases and supply stays the same?', 'The law of supply and demand is one of the most fundamental principles in economics. When a product is in high demand but supply is limited, sellers can charge higher prices because buyers are competing for a scarce resource. When supply is plentiful but demand is low, prices tend to fall as sellers compete to attract buyers. The point where the quantity sellers want to sell equals the quantity buyers want to buy is called the equilibrium price. In the real world, prices shift constantly as supply and demand change — a drought that reduces the wheat harvest, for example, raises bread prices, while a new technology that makes production cheaper can lower them.', '["Prices fall because sellers want to attract buyers", "Prices stay the same regardless of demand", "Prices rise because buyers are competing for a limited supply", "Prices become unpredictable and fluctuate randomly"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage states: "When a product is in high demand but supply is limited, sellers can charge higher prices because buyers are competing for a scarce resource."')

,('reading', 'What does "equilibrium" most likely mean as used in the passage?', 'The law of supply and demand is one of the most fundamental principles in economics. When a product is in high demand but supply is limited, sellers can charge higher prices because buyers are competing for a scarce resource. When supply is plentiful but demand is low, prices tend to fall as sellers compete to attract buyers. The point where the quantity sellers want to sell equals the quantity buyers want to buy is called the equilibrium price. In the real world, prices shift constantly as supply and demand change — a drought that reduces the wheat harvest, for example, raises bread prices, while a new technology that makes production cheaper can lower them.', '["The highest price a product has ever sold for", "A point of balance where supply and demand are equal", "The price set by the government for a product", "The average price of all products in an economy"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage defines equilibrium price as the point where "the quantity sellers want to sell equals the quantity buyers want to buy" — a state of balance.')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred about the effect of a new technology that makes production much cheaper?', 'The law of supply and demand is one of the most fundamental principles in economics. When a product is in high demand but supply is limited, sellers can charge higher prices because buyers are competing for a scarce resource. When supply is plentiful but demand is low, prices tend to fall as sellers compete to attract buyers. The point where the quantity sellers want to sell equals the quantity buyers want to buy is called the equilibrium price. In the real world, prices shift constantly as supply and demand change — a drought that reduces the wheat harvest, for example, raises bread prices, while a new technology that makes production cheaper can lower them.', '["It would cause demand to fall because buyers would not trust cheaper products", "It would likely increase supply and lower prices for consumers", "It would have no effect on prices if demand stays the same", "It would cause sellers to raise prices to make more profit"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'The passage states cheaper production can lower prices. Cheaper production also enables sellers to produce more, increasing supply — and the passage''s own framework shows more supply with stable demand leads to lower prices.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage?', 'The law of supply and demand is one of the most fundamental principles in economics. When a product is in high demand but supply is limited, sellers can charge higher prices because buyers are competing for a scarce resource. When supply is plentiful but demand is low, prices tend to fall as sellers compete to attract buyers. The point where the quantity sellers want to sell equals the quantity buyers want to buy is called the equilibrium price. In the real world, prices shift constantly as supply and demand change — a drought that reduces the wheat harvest, for example, raises bread prices, while a new technology that makes production cheaper can lower them.', '["Droughts and technology are the biggest threats to a healthy economy", "Sellers always have more power than buyers in setting prices", "Supply and demand are the forces that determine prices in a market economy", "The equilibrium price never changes once it is established"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The passage introduces supply and demand as the key forces controlling prices, explains how they work, and gives examples — option C captures this main economic concept.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, which city is considered the birthplace of democracy?', 'Democracy — the system of government in which citizens hold political power — traces its origins to ancient Athens, Greece, in the 5th century BCE. Athenian statesman Cleisthenes introduced reforms that gave citizens a direct voice in governing the city-state, replacing the rule of aristocrats with a system called direct democracy. In this system, eligible citizens gathered in an assembly and voted on laws and policies themselves, rather than electing representatives. However, participation was limited: women, enslaved people, and foreigners were excluded. Despite these flaws, ancient Athens established the foundational idea that ordinary people, not only kings or nobles, had the right to shape their own government.', '["Rome", "Sparta", "Athens", "Alexandria"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage directly states that democracy "traces its origins to ancient Athens, Greece."')

,('reading', 'What does "direct democracy" mean as described in the passage?', 'Democracy — the system of government in which citizens hold political power — traces its origins to ancient Athens, Greece, in the 5th century BCE. Athenian statesman Cleisthenes introduced reforms that gave citizens a direct voice in governing the city-state, replacing the rule of aristocrats with a system called direct democracy. In this system, eligible citizens gathered in an assembly and voted on laws and policies themselves, rather than electing representatives. However, participation was limited: women, enslaved people, and foreigners were excluded. Despite these flaws, ancient Athens established the foundational idea that ordinary people, not only kings or nobles, had the right to shape their own government.', '["Electing representatives to vote on laws on your behalf", "Citizens voting directly on laws and policies themselves", "A king ruling with the advice of citizens", "A council of nobles making decisions for the public"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage defines direct democracy as citizens who "voted on laws and policies themselves, rather than electing representatives."')

,('reading', 'Why does the author describe Athens'' democracy as having "flaws" in the final sentence?', 'Democracy — the system of government in which citizens hold political power — traces its origins to ancient Athens, Greece, in the 5th century BCE. Athenian statesman Cleisthenes introduced reforms that gave citizens a direct voice in governing the city-state, replacing the rule of aristocrats with a system called direct democracy. In this system, eligible citizens gathered in an assembly and voted on laws and policies themselves, rather than electing representatives. However, participation was limited: women, enslaved people, and foreigners were excluded. Despite these flaws, ancient Athens established the foundational idea that ordinary people, not only kings or nobles, had the right to shape their own government.', '["To argue that Athens was not really a democracy at all", "To acknowledge that Athenian democracy excluded many people, even while praising its foundational ideas", "To show that Cleisthenes was a dishonest leader", "To suggest that ancient systems are not worth studying"]'::jsonb, 1, 3, 'By acknowledging the exclusion of women, enslaved people, and foreigners, the author gives a balanced view — celebrating a founding idea while honestly noting its significant limitations.')

,('reading', 'What is the passage mainly about?', 'Democracy — the system of government in which citizens hold political power — traces its origins to ancient Athens, Greece, in the 5th century BCE. Athenian statesman Cleisthenes introduced reforms that gave citizens a direct voice in governing the city-state, replacing the rule of aristocrats with a system called direct democracy. In this system, eligible citizens gathered in an assembly and voted on laws and policies themselves, rather than electing representatives. However, participation was limited: women, enslaved people, and foreigners were excluded. Despite these flaws, ancient Athens established the foundational idea that ordinary people, not only kings or nobles, had the right to shape their own government.', '["The biography of Cleisthenes and his political career", "The origins of democracy in ancient Athens, including both its innovations and its limitations", "Why democracy failed in ancient Greece", "The differences between ancient and modern voting systems"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage covers where democracy began, how it worked, who was excluded, and its lasting significance — option B captures the full scope.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, how do antibiotics fight bacterial infections?', 'Antibiotics are medicines that fight bacterial infections by targeting features of bacteria that human cells do not have. Some antibiotics work by disrupting the construction of a bacterium''s cell wall — without a protective wall, the bacterium bursts and dies. Others interfere with the bacteria''s ability to copy their genetic material or produce essential proteins, effectively stopping reproduction. Antibiotics do not work against viruses, which is why doctors do not prescribe them for colds or the flu. Overusing antibiotics has led to a growing problem called antibiotic resistance, in which bacteria evolve to survive the drugs that once killed them — a serious threat to public health worldwide.', '["By strengthening the immune system to fight infections faster", "By targeting features of bacteria that human cells lack, such as cell walls and protein production", "By killing all microorganisms in the body, including helpful bacteria", "By lowering body temperature to slow bacterial growth"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explains that antibiotics target bacterial features — like cell walls — that human cells don''t have, and disrupt reproduction. Option B captures this precisely.')

,('reading', 'What does "antibiotic resistance" mean as described in the passage?', 'Antibiotics are medicines that fight bacterial infections by targeting features of bacteria that human cells do not have. Some antibiotics work by disrupting the construction of a bacterium''s cell wall — without a protective wall, the bacterium bursts and dies. Others interfere with the bacteria''s ability to copy their genetic material or produce essential proteins, effectively stopping reproduction. Antibiotics do not work against viruses, which is why doctors do not prescribe them for colds or the flu. Overusing antibiotics has led to a growing problem called antibiotic resistance, in which bacteria evolve to survive the drugs that once killed them — a serious threat to public health worldwide.', '["Patients refusing to take prescribed antibiotics", "Bacteria that have evolved to survive antibiotic drugs", "Antibiotics that no longer dissolve in the body", "A shortage of antibiotic medications in hospitals"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage defines it directly: bacteria that "evolve to survive the drugs that once killed them." Option B restates this definition.')

,('reading', 'Why do doctors not prescribe antibiotics for colds or the flu?', 'Antibiotics are medicines that fight bacterial infections by targeting features of bacteria that human cells do not have. Some antibiotics work by disrupting the construction of a bacterium''s cell wall — without a protective wall, the bacterium bursts and dies. Others interfere with the bacteria''s ability to copy their genetic material or produce essential proteins, effectively stopping reproduction. Antibiotics do not work against viruses, which is why doctors do not prescribe them for colds or the flu. Overusing antibiotics has led to a growing problem called antibiotic resistance, in which bacteria evolve to survive the drugs that once killed them — a serious threat to public health worldwide.', '["Colds and flu are not serious enough to need medicine", "Colds and flu are caused by viruses, not bacteria, so antibiotics would not work", "Antibiotics are too expensive to use for minor illnesses", "Doctors prefer natural remedies for respiratory infections"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage states: "Antibiotics do not work against viruses" — and colds and flu are viral infections, so prescribing antibiotics for them would be ineffective.')

,('reading', 'What might happen if antibiotics are overused, based on the passage?', 'Antibiotics are medicines that fight bacterial infections by targeting features of bacteria that human cells do not have. Some antibiotics work by disrupting the construction of a bacterium''s cell wall — without a protective wall, the bacterium bursts and dies. Others interfere with the bacteria''s ability to copy their genetic material or produce essential proteins, effectively stopping reproduction. Antibiotics do not work against viruses, which is why doctors do not prescribe them for colds or the flu. Overusing antibiotics has led to a growing problem called antibiotic resistance, in which bacteria evolve to survive the drugs that once killed them — a serious threat to public health worldwide.', '["Antibiotics would become more effective over time", "Bacteria would evolve resistance, making infections harder to treat", "Viruses would start responding to antibiotic treatment", "People would develop immunity to bacterial infections naturally"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage directly states that overusing antibiotics leads to antibiotic resistance — bacteria that can survive the drugs, making infections far harder to treat.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what role do coral reefs play in the ocean?', 'Coral reefs are often called the "rainforests of the sea" because they support an extraordinary diversity of life despite covering less than one percent of the ocean floor. Reef-building corals are tiny animals that live in partnership with algae, which provide the corals with energy through photosynthesis. The hard calcium carbonate skeletons that corals build over thousands of years create a complex habitat where thousands of fish and invertebrate species find food and shelter. Reefs also protect coastlines from storm waves and support fishing industries worth billions of dollars worldwide. Rising ocean temperatures caused by climate change cause "coral bleaching," in which stressed corals expel their algae and may die, threatening the entire ecosystem.', '["They serve as feeding grounds exclusively for large ocean predators", "They support enormous biodiversity, protect coastlines, and sustain fishing economies", "They produce the oxygen that marine animals breathe", "They are found mainly in the deep ocean far from human populations"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage lists multiple roles: biodiversity support, coastline protection, and economic value for fishing industries — option B is the most complete summary of these functions.')

,('reading', 'What does "bleaching" suggest about coral reefs when ocean temperatures rise?', 'Coral reefs are often called the "rainforests of the sea" because they support an extraordinary diversity of life despite covering less than one percent of the ocean floor. Reef-building corals are tiny animals that live in partnership with algae, which provide the corals with energy through photosynthesis. The hard calcium carbonate skeletons that corals build over thousands of years create a complex habitat where thousands of fish and invertebrate species find food and shelter. Reefs also protect coastlines from storm waves and support fishing industries worth billions of dollars worldwide. Rising ocean temperatures caused by climate change cause "coral bleaching," in which stressed corals expel their algae and may die, threatening the entire ecosystem.', '["Corals turn brighter colors when they are healthy", "Corals lose their algae and energy source, which can cause them to die", "Warm water causes corals to grow faster", "Bleaching is a natural seasonal event that does not harm reefs"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage explains bleaching as corals expelling their algae — since the algae provide energy, losing them starves the coral, which "may die," threatening the ecosystem.')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred about the relationship between corals and algae?', 'Coral reefs are often called the "rainforests of the sea" because they support an extraordinary diversity of life despite covering less than one percent of the ocean floor. Reef-building corals are tiny animals that live in partnership with algae, which provide the corals with energy through photosynthesis. The hard calcium carbonate skeletons that corals build over thousands of years create a complex habitat where thousands of fish and invertebrate species find food and shelter. Reefs also protect coastlines from storm waves and support fishing industries worth billions of dollars worldwide. Rising ocean temperatures caused by climate change cause "coral bleaching," in which stressed corals expel their algae and may die, threatening the entire ecosystem.', '["Algae compete with coral for space on the reef", "Coral cannot survive without the energy algae provide through photosynthesis", "Algae are harmful to corals and cause bleaching", "Algae and coral are the same type of organism"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The algae provide corals with energy through photosynthesis. When corals expel algae due to stress, they "may die" — this shows corals depend on algae to survive.')

,('reading', 'What is the passage mainly about?', 'Coral reefs are often called the "rainforests of the sea" because they support an extraordinary diversity of life despite covering less than one percent of the ocean floor. Reef-building corals are tiny animals that live in partnership with algae, which provide the corals with energy through photosynthesis. The hard calcium carbonate skeletons that corals build over thousands of years create a complex habitat where thousands of fish and invertebrate species find food and shelter. Reefs also protect coastlines from storm waves and support fishing industries worth billions of dollars worldwide. Rising ocean temperatures caused by climate change cause "coral bleaching," in which stressed corals expel their algae and may die, threatening the entire ecosystem.', '["Why fishing near coral reefs should be banned", "The structure, importance, and threats facing coral reef ecosystems", "How algae reproduce in warm ocean water", "The history of scientific research on coral reefs"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage describes what coral reefs are, their ecological and economic importance, how they work, and the threat of climate change — option B covers all of these elements.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, how does sound travel from its source to your ears?', 'Sound is a form of energy that travels as waves — but unlike light, it cannot travel through empty space. When an object vibrates, it pushes against nearby air molecules, creating areas of compression and expansion that ripple outward from the source. These pressure waves travel through the air — or through solids and liquids — until they reach the ear, where they cause the eardrum to vibrate. The brain interprets these vibrations as sound. The speed of sound depends on the medium it travels through: it moves faster through water than air, and faster through steel than water. The pitch of a sound is determined by the frequency of the waves — more waves per second produce a higher pitch.', '["Sound travels as light waves that are converted into vibrations by the ear", "Sound travels as pressure waves created by vibrations, which cause the eardrum to vibrate", "Sound jumps directly from the source to the eardrum without a medium", "Sound travels through space and is slowed down when it enters the atmosphere"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage explains that vibrating objects create pressure waves that travel through a medium and cause the eardrum to vibrate — option B accurately summarizes this process.')

,('reading', 'What does "frequency" mean as used in the passage about sound?', 'Sound is a form of energy that travels as waves — but unlike light, it cannot travel through empty space. When an object vibrates, it pushes against nearby air molecules, creating areas of compression and expansion that ripple outward from the source. These pressure waves travel through the air — or through solids and liquids — until they reach the ear, where they cause the eardrum to vibrate. The brain interprets these vibrations as sound. The speed of sound depends on the medium it travels through: it moves faster through water than air, and faster through steel than water. The pitch of a sound is determined by the frequency of the waves — more waves per second produce a higher pitch.', '["The loudness or volume of a sound", "How many waves pass a point per second", "The distance a sound wave travels", "The material through which sound travels"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage links frequency directly to pitch, saying "more waves per second produce a higher pitch" — frequency is the number of waves per second.')

,('reading', 'What would most likely happen to the pitch of a sound if its frequency doubled?', 'Sound is a form of energy that travels as waves — but unlike light, it cannot travel through empty space. When an object vibrates, it pushes against nearby air molecules, creating areas of compression and expansion that ripple outward from the source. These pressure waves travel through the air — or through solids and liquids — until they reach the ear, where they cause the eardrum to vibrate. The brain interprets these vibrations as sound. The speed of sound depends on the medium it travels through: it moves faster through water than air, and faster through steel than water. The pitch of a sound is determined by the frequency of the waves — more waves per second produce a higher pitch.', '["The pitch would get lower", "The pitch would stay the same", "The pitch would get higher", "The sound would stop traveling through air"]'::jsonb, 2, 2, 'The passage states more waves per second produce a higher pitch. If frequency doubles, the number of waves per second doubles, so the pitch would rise.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage?', 'Sound is a form of energy that travels as waves — but unlike light, it cannot travel through empty space. When an object vibrates, it pushes against nearby air molecules, creating areas of compression and expansion that ripple outward from the source. These pressure waves travel through the air — or through solids and liquids — until they reach the ear, where they cause the eardrum to vibrate. The brain interprets these vibrations as sound. The speed of sound depends on the medium it travels through: it moves faster through water than air, and faster through steel than water. The pitch of a sound is determined by the frequency of the waves — more waves per second produce a higher pitch.', '["Why sound cannot travel in outer space", "How sound waves are produced, how they travel, and how their properties determine pitch", "The anatomy of the human ear and how it is protected", "Why some materials conduct electricity better than others"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage covers how sound is produced, how it travels through different media, how the ear receives it, and what determines pitch — option B best covers the full main idea.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, what triggers many birds'' migration each year?', 'Every autumn, millions of birds across the world undertake remarkable journeys, traveling hundreds or thousands of miles to reach warmer climates where food remains available. Unlike most behaviors, bird migration appears to be triggered not by cold temperatures directly, but by changes in day length — called photoperiod — which signals the approaching season. Birds navigate using a combination of the sun''s position, star patterns at night, Earth''s magnetic field, and familiar landmarks. Many species return to the same nesting grounds year after year with extraordinary precision. Scientists are still studying exactly how birds integrate all of these navigational cues, but it is clear that migration is a finely tuned biological response to environmental change.', '["Dropping temperatures in autumn", "The start of rainfall in their habitat", "Changes in the length of daylight hours", "Decreasing food supply in summer"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage directly states that migration is triggered by "changes in day length — called photoperiod — which signals the approaching season," not by cold temperatures directly.')

,('reading', 'What does "photoperiod" mean as used in the passage about bird migration?', 'Every autumn, millions of birds across the world undertake remarkable journeys, traveling hundreds or thousands of miles to reach warmer climates where food remains available. Unlike most behaviors, bird migration appears to be triggered not by cold temperatures directly, but by changes in day length — called photoperiod — which signals the approaching season. Birds navigate using a combination of the sun''s position, star patterns at night, Earth''s magnetic field, and familiar landmarks. Many species return to the same nesting grounds year after year with extraordinary precision. Scientists are still studying exactly how birds integrate all of these navigational cues, but it is clear that migration is a finely tuned biological response to environmental change.', '["The total amount of rainfall in a season", "The length of daylight in a given period", "A bird''s internal sense of direction", "The temperature difference between two seasons"]'::jsonb, 1, 1, 'The passage defines photoperiod right in the text: "changes in day length — called photoperiod."')

,('reading', 'What can be inferred about birds that return to the same nesting grounds each year?', 'Every autumn, millions of birds across the world undertake remarkable journeys, traveling hundreds or thousands of miles to reach warmer climates where food remains available. Unlike most behaviors, bird migration appears to be triggered not by cold temperatures directly, but by changes in day length — called photoperiod — which signals the approaching season. Birds navigate using a combination of the sun''s position, star patterns at night, Earth''s magnetic field, and familiar landmarks. Many species return to the same nesting grounds year after year with extraordinary precision. Scientists are still studying exactly how birds integrate all of these navigational cues, but it is clear that migration is a finely tuned biological response to environmental change.', '["They never encounter any obstacles during migration", "They rely entirely on learned behavior from older birds", "They possess a reliable internal navigation system that stores location information", "They are guided to their nesting grounds by other animals"]'::jsonb, 2, 3, 'Returning to the exact same location across thousands of miles with "extraordinary precision" implies birds have an effective internal system for storing and using navigational information.')

,('reading', 'What is the passage primarily about?', 'Every autumn, millions of birds across the world undertake remarkable journeys, traveling hundreds or thousands of miles to reach warmer climates where food remains available. Unlike most behaviors, bird migration appears to be triggered not by cold temperatures directly, but by changes in day length — called photoperiod — which signals the approaching season. Birds navigate using a combination of the sun''s position, star patterns at night, Earth''s magnetic field, and familiar landmarks. Many species return to the same nesting grounds year after year with extraordinary precision. Scientists are still studying exactly how birds integrate all of these navigational cues, but it is clear that migration is a finely tuned biological response to environmental change.', '["The threats that climate change poses to migrating birds", "What triggers bird migration and how birds navigate during their journeys", "Why some birds migrate while others do not", "The specific routes used by different bird species"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage focuses on what causes migration (photoperiod) and how birds navigate — option B captures both elements of the main idea.')

,('reading', 'According to the passage, where are memories first formed?', 'Memory is not stored in a single location in the brain, but it begins in a region called the hippocampus. When we experience something new, the hippocampus helps encode the information by strengthening connections between neurons — the brain''s nerve cells. Initially, memories are fragile and can be disrupted. Over time, through a process called consolidation, memories are gradually transferred to the cerebral cortex, the brain''s outer layer, for long-term storage. Sleep plays a critical role in this process: during sleep, the brain replays recent experiences and strengthens the neural pathways that hold them. Strong emotional experiences tend to form more vivid and lasting memories because the amygdala — the brain''s emotional center — helps flag them as important.', '["The cerebral cortex", "The amygdala", "The hippocampus", "The nervous system outside the brain"]'::jsonb, 2, 1, 'The passage states that memory "begins in a region called the hippocampus," which helps encode new information.')

,('reading', 'What does "consolidation" mean as used in the passage about memory?', 'Memory is not stored in a single location in the brain, but it begins in a region called the hippocampus. When we experience something new, the hippocampus helps encode the information by strengthening connections between neurons — the brain''s nerve cells. Initially, memories are fragile and can be disrupted. Over time, through a process called consolidation, memories are gradually transferred to the cerebral cortex, the brain''s outer layer, for long-term storage. Sleep plays a critical role in this process: during sleep, the brain replays recent experiences and strengthens the neural pathways that hold them. Strong emotional experiences tend to form more vivid and lasting memories because the amygdala — the brain''s emotional center — helps flag them as important.', '["The process of forgetting old memories to make room for new ones", "The gradual transfer and stabilization of memories into long-term storage", "The experience of recalling a memory under stress", "The destruction of memories during sleep"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage describes consolidation as the process by which memories are "gradually transferred to the cerebral cortex...for long-term storage" and strengthened over time.')

,('reading', 'Why do strong emotional experiences tend to create more lasting memories?', 'Memory is not stored in a single location in the brain, but it begins in a region called the hippocampus. When we experience something new, the hippocampus helps encode the information by strengthening connections between neurons — the brain''s nerve cells. Initially, memories are fragile and can be disrupted. Over time, through a process called consolidation, memories are gradually transferred to the cerebral cortex, the brain''s outer layer, for long-term storage. Sleep plays a critical role in this process: during sleep, the brain replays recent experiences and strengthens the neural pathways that hold them. Strong emotional experiences tend to form more vivid and lasting memories because the amygdala — the brain''s emotional center — helps flag them as important.', '["The hippocampus stores emotional memories in a different location", "The amygdala signals that emotional events are important, making them more strongly encoded", "People pay more attention to boring events than emotional ones", "Emotional memories skip the hippocampus and go directly to long-term storage"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage explains that the amygdala "helps flag them as important" — this signal causes emotional memories to be more strongly encoded and retained.')

,('reading', 'What is the main idea of this passage?', 'Memory is not stored in a single location in the brain, but it begins in a region called the hippocampus. When we experience something new, the hippocampus helps encode the information by strengthening connections between neurons — the brain''s nerve cells. Initially, memories are fragile and can be disrupted. Over time, through a process called consolidation, memories are gradually transferred to the cerebral cortex, the brain''s outer layer, for long-term storage. Sleep plays a critical role in this process: during sleep, the brain replays recent experiences and strengthens the neural pathways that hold them. Strong emotional experiences tend to form more vivid and lasting memories because the amygdala — the brain''s emotional center — helps flag them as important.', '["The hippocampus is the only part of the brain that matters for learning", "The brain forms and stores memories through a multi-step process involving several regions", "Sleep is the most important factor in how smart a person is", "Emotions are stored separately from other types of memories"]'::jsonb, 1, 2, 'The passage traces memory formation from the hippocampus through consolidation to long-term storage, mentioning the roles of sleep and the amygdala — option B accurately captures this multi-step, multi-region process.');
